{"title_page": "Sepala Attygalle", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = [[General (Sri Lanka)|General]] [[Deshamanya]]\n|name= Don Sepala Attygalle\n|honorific_suffix=[[Royal Victorian Order|LVO]], [[Sri Lanka Armoured Corps|SLAC]]\n|birth_date= 1922\n|death_date= January 2001\n|birth_place= \n|death_place=\n|placeofburial= \n|placeofburial_label= \n|image= Lt Gen Attygalle.jpg\n|image_size= 200\n|caption= General Deshamanya Sepala Attygalle, LVO, SLAC\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= [[Sri Lanka]]\n|serviceyears= 1942\u20131977                  \n|rank=[[General (Sri Lanka)|General]] \n|branch=\n{{plainlist|\n*[[Ceylon Defence Force]]\n*[[Ceylon Army]]\n*[[Sri Lanka Army]]\n}}\n|commands=\n{{plainlist|\n*[[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]]\n*[[Chief of Staff]] of the Sri Lankan Army\n}}\n|unit=\n{{plainlist|\n*<!-- Commented out: [[File:SLLI Crest.gif|25px]] -->[[Ceylon Light Infantry]]\n*[[Sri Lanka Armoured Corps]]\n}}\n|battles=\n{{plainlist|\n*[[World War II]]\n*[[1971 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|1971 Insurrection]]\n}}\n|awards{{plainlist|\n*[[Royal Victorian Order|Lieutenant of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n*[[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]\n}}\n|laterwork= [[Permanent Secretary]] [[Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka)|Ministry of Defence]], <br/> [[Sri Lankan High Commissioner to the United Kingdom]] \n}}\n[[General (Sri Lanka)|General]]  [[Deshamanya]] '''Don Sepala Attygalle''', [[Royal Victorian Order|LVO]], [[Imperial Defence College|idc]], [[psc (British Army)|psc]], [[Sri Lanka Armoured Corps|SLAC]] (1922 \u2013 January 2001) was a [[Sri Lanka]]n [[Commissioned officer|military leader]], [[civil servant]] and [[diplomat]]. The longest serving [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]] (1967\u20131977), he went on to serve as the [[Permanent secretary]] to the [[Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka)|Ministry of Defence]] and Sri Lankan [[High Commissioner]] to the [[United Kingdom]].\n\nHe is most notable for successfully crushing the [[1971 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|1971 Insurrection]] in a matter of months and becoming the first Sri Lankan army officer to be promoted to the rank of a [[General officer|four star General]]. He is known as the ''\"Father of the Armoured Corps\"'' and was [[Equerry|The Equerry]] to [[Elizabeth II|The Queen]] during her [[Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II|coronation]] in 1953.\n\n==Early life==\nSepala Attygalle was educated at the [[Royal College, Colombo]] where he became the [[Head Prefect|head prefect]], won colours in both [[Sport of athletics|athletics]] and [[rugby union|rugby]]; and was the Senior Sergeant of the [[Royal College, Colombo#Cadet Contingent|Cadet Contingent of Royal]]. After completing schooling, he entered the [[University College, Colombo]].<ref>[http://www.priu.gov.lk/news_update/Current_Affairs/CA200101/20010117SL_Army_commanders.htm Last post for two Generals] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107084513/http://www.priu.gov.lk/news_update/Current_Affairs/CA200101/20010117SL_Army_commanders.htm |date=7 January 2009 }}</ref> \n\nUThereafter he went on to study at the [[University of Ceylon]].\nHe graduated from the [[Staff College, Camberley]] in 1953 and the [[Imperial Defence College]] in 1966.\n\n==Military career==\n===Second World War===\nWith the outbreak of [[World War II]] seeking a [[Officer (armed forces)#United Kingdom|King's Commission]], he left his studies at the university college to joined as a [[Cadet Officer|cadet officer]] undergoing basic officer training at [[Diyatalawa]]. He took the [[Sword of Honour (Sandhurst)|sword of honour]] at the army passing out parade in 1941 and was commissioned as a [[second lieutenant]] in the [[Ceylon Light Infantry]]. He thereafter underwent advanced training in India.\n\n===Civil service===\nAfter the war, he was demobilized and joined the civil service serving as [[Assistant controller|Assistant Controller]] of Textiles and Assistant Controller of Exports and Imports.\n\n===Ceylon army===\nWith the formation of the new [[Ceylon Army]] in 1949 following the passing of the ''Army Act''; he joined it and was commissioned as a [[lieutenant]] in the 1 Battalion, [[Ceylon Light Infantry]] as a regular officer, promoted to the rank of [[Captain (land and air)|captain]] on the same day he was assigned was as the [[General Staff Officer]] - Grade 3 (GSO3), in the [[Army Headquarters, Ceylon]]. In 1950 he was appointed as an extra [[Aide-de-camp]] (ADC) to [[Herwald Ramsbotham, 1st Viscount Soulbury|Lord Soulbury]], the [[Governor General of Ceylon]], succeeding Major [[Bevis Bawa]]. He was promoted to rank of [[major]] in 1952.  \n\nIn mid 1952, he attended the Company Commanders' Course at the [[Warminster|School of Infantry, Warminster]] and the Land/Air Warfare Course at the [[School of Land/Air Warfare]]. Thereafter he was attached to the 1st Battalion, [[King's Own Yorkshire Light Infantry]], in Germany; serving with the [[Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe|NATO Forces in Europe]]. On his return he was re-assigned as a staff officer in the general staff at [[Army Headquarters (Sri Lanka)|army headquarters]].  \n\nIn 1953, he relinquished his staff appointment at the army headquarters and left for the [[United Kingdom]] to attend the [[Staff College, Camberley]]. On completing the staff course, he was seconded to the [[1st The Queen's Dragoon Guards]]. During this time he was appointed [[Equerry]] to HM [[Queen Elizabeth II]] at her coronation and also served as military liaison officer ([[Military attach\u00e9|military attach\u00e9]]) to the [[Sri Lankan High Commissioner to the United Kingdom|High Commissioner for Ceylon]] in the United Kingdom. On his return to Ceylon, he took up command of the [[Echelon Barracks]].\n\n===Ceylon Armoured Corps===\nOn 10 October 1955, Major D.S. Attygalle raised the 1st Reconnaissance (Recce) Squadron as the [[Cavalry|Cavalry Arm]] in the Ceylon Army in the lines of 1st The Queen's Dragoon Guards. On 17 December 1955 a Combined Services Buddhist Mission led by Major Attygalle left for [[Burma]] on board [[HMCyS Vijaya]], to represent the [[Armed Forces of Ceylon]] at the [[Buddha's Birthday|Buddha Jayanthi]] commemoration celebrations, and present a gift of a [[Jaya Sri Maha Bodhi|Bodhi tree sapling]]. In 1958, the [[Squadron (army)|recce squadron]] was expanded to a [[regiment]] and Attygalle was appointed as its first commanding officer with the rank of [[lieutenant colonel]]. The 1st Reconnaissance Regiment became the core of the [[Sri Lanka Armoured Corps|Ceylon Armoured Corps]].\n\n===TFAII and Chief of Staff===\nIn 1962, he was promoted to the rank of [[colonel]]; he took up command of the [[Panagoda Cantonment]], whilst serving as commanding officer, Ceylon Armoured Corps. Thereafter he became the commander of the [[Task Force Anti Illicit Immigration]] in 1963, later the inspector of training, Army Headquarters. He became the [[Chief of Staff]] of the army in 1964 after relinquishing command of the Ceylon Armoured Corps and relinquished command of the Task Force Anti Illicit Immigration in 1965.\n\n===Commander of the Army===\nOn 1 October 1967 [[Brigadier]] Don S. Attygalle took over as the Acting Commander of the Army after the retirement of [[Major General]] [[B.R. Heyn]]. Promoted to the rank of [[major general]], he was confirmed as [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Army]] shortly. Under his leadership the army crushed the [[1971 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|1971 Insurrection]] within two months, and he was promoted to the rank of [[lieutenant general]] on 4 April 1974, thus being the first officer of the [[Sri Lanka Army]] to hold this rank. When he retired on 13 October 1977, after having served for ten years as commander, he was promoted to the rank of [[General officer|general]], thus becoming the first Sri Lankan army officer to hold the rank of a four-star general and longest-serving Commander of the Army.\n\n==Later life==\n===Ministry of Defence===\nOn retirement from the army, he took up appointment as Additional Secretary, Ministry of Defence and Chief Co-ordinating Authority in the Ministry of Defence in 1977. \n\n===Secretary of Defence===\nIn the early 1980s, with the escalation of the [[Sri Lankan Civil War|Tamil Militancy]], he was appointed as [[permanent secretary]], [[Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka)|Ministry of Defence]] and served as National Defence Advisor to the [[President of Sri Lanka]]. He played a major role during the [[Vadamarachchi Operation]] until Indian intervention stopped it midway.  During this time he was the founding chairman, Air Ports and Aviation Services and chairman of [[Air Lanka]]. \n\n===High Commissioner to the United Kingdom===\nIn 1990 he was appointed as [[Sri Lankan High Commissioner to the United Kingdom|High Commissioner for Sri Lanka]] in the United Kingdom.\n\n===Death===\nHis [[military funeral]] in January 2001 was well attended by his family, friends and colleagues who gathered to mourn his loss.\n\n==Family== \nHe was married to Mrs Brighty Attygalle who died in July 2010, they had one son Suraj and two grandsons Damin and Shaminda. His brother was Dr Gamini Attygalle, [[FRCS]] a leading [[anaesthesiologist]] who was married to Kalyani Wijewardene, daughter of Don Walter T Wijewardene and sister of [[Upali Wijewardene]].<ref>[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/100103/Plus/plus_11.html A distinguished doctor who was respected for his rare qualities]</ref>\n\n==Decorations ==\nHe was made a Member of the [[Royal Victorian Order]] (Military Division) (MVO) by Her Majesty the Queen in recognition of the services rendered by him, during her Majesty's visit to Ceylon in 1954 which was later upgrade to lieutenant in 1984. For wartime service in World War II, he had earned the [[Defence Medal (United Kingdom)|Defence Medal]] and the [[War Medal 1939\u20131945]], and for service in the Ceylon Army, he received the [[Ceylon Armed Services Long Service Medal]], the [[Queen Elizabeth II Coronation Medal]] and the [[Ceylon Armed Services Inauguration Medal]]. For service in the Sri Lanka Army, he received the [[Republic of Sri Lanka Armed Services Medal]] and the [[Vadamarachchi Operation Medal]] for his later service as Secretary of Defence.\n\n===Honors===\n* Attygalle was promoted to the rank of [[General officer|general]] upon his retirement in 1977.\n* He was awarded the title [[Deshamanya]] from the Government of Sri Lanka.\n* He was a made a [[Royal Victorian Order|Member of the Royal Victorian Order]], which was later upgraded to Lieutenant.\n* Doctor of Literature (honorary) by the [[University of Sri Lanka]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sri Lanka Armoured Corps]]\n*[[Sri Lankan Non Career Diplomats]]\n*[[List of Sri Lankan non-career Permanent Secretaries]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080505203152/http://www.army.lk/co.php Parade Commander Major B.R. Heyn, CLI]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110904090717/http://www.armouredcorps.lk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=26:deshamanya-general-ds-atiygalle-mvo-idc-psc-d-litt&catid=7:retaired-senior-officers&Itemid=4 Father of the Armoured Corps]\n*[http://www.island.lk/2001/01/17/news05.html From Captain to Army Commander \u2014 Sepala Attygalle\u2019s illustrious career]\n*[http://www.rootsweb.com/~lkawgw/comcork.html rootsweb.com]\n*[http://suntimes.lk/040118/plus/appreciation.html SundayTimes Appreciation]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[http://ceylonmedals.com/attygalle.htm Deshamanya General Don Sepala Attygalle LVO ADC idc psc]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]]\n | before=[[B.R. Heyn]]\n | after=[[Denis Perera]]| years=1967 - 1977}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{succession box | title=Sri Lanka's High Commissioner to the United Kingdom | before=? | after=? | years= }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Commanders of the Sri Lankan Army}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Attygalle, D.S.}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan generals]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese civil servants]]\n[[Category:Equerries]]\n[[Category:Lieutenants of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Royal College, Colombo]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Ceylon (Colombo)]]\n[[Category:Ceylonese military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of Sri Lanka to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Defence Studies]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Staff College, Camberley]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Sri Lanka Army]]\n[[Category:King's Own Yorkshire Light Infantry officers]]\n[[Category:1st The Queen's Dragoon Guards officers]]\n[[Category:Sri Lanka Armoured Corps officers]]\n[[Category:Permanent secretaries of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan military attach\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:Deshamanya]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = [[General (Sri Lanka)|General]] [[Deshamanya]]\n|name= Don Sepala Attygalle\n|honorific_suffix=[[Royal Victorian Order|LVO]], [[Sri Lanka Armoured Corps|SLAC]]\n|birth_date= 1922\n|death_date= January 2001\n|birth_place= \n|death_place=\n|placeofburial= \n|placeofburial_label= \n|image= Lt Gen Attygalle.jpg\n|image_size= 200\n|caption= General Deshamanya Sepala Attygalle, LVO, SLAC\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= {{flagicon|Sri Lanka}} [[Sri Lanka]]\n|serviceyears= 1942\u20131977                  \n|rank=[[General (Sri Lanka)|General]] \n|branch=\n{{plainlist|\n*[[Ceylon Defence Force]]\n*[[Ceylon Army]]\n*[[Sri Lanka Army]]\n}}\n|commands=\n{{plainlist|\n*[[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]]\n*[[Chief of Staff]] of the Sri Lankan Army\n}}\n|unit=\n{{plainlist|\n*<!-- Commented out: [[File:SLLI Crest.gif|25px]] -->[[Ceylon Light Infantry]]\n*[[Sri Lanka Armoured Corps]]\n}}\n|battles=\n{{plainlist|\n*[[World War II]]\n*[[1971 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|1971 Insurrection]]\n}}\n|awards{{plainlist|\n*[[Royal Victorian Order|Lieutenant of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n*[[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]\n}}\n|laterwork= [[Permanent Secretary]] [[Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka)|Ministry of Defence]], <br/> [[Sri Lankan High Commissioner to the United Kingdom]] \n}}\n[[General (Sri Lanka)|General]]  [[Deshamanya]] '''Don Sepala Attygalle''', [[Royal Victorian Order|LVO]], [[Imperial Defence College|idc]], [[psc (British Army)|psc]], [[Sri Lanka Armoured Corps|SLAC]] (1922 \u2013 January 2001) was a [[Sri Lanka]]n [[Commissioned officer|military leader]], [[civil servant]] and [[diplomat]]. The longest serving [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]] (1967\u20131977), he went on to serve as the [[Permanent secretary]] to the [[Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka)|Ministry of Defence]] and Sri Lankan [[High Commissioner]] to the [[United Kingdom]].\n\nHe is most notable for successfully crushing the [[1971 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|1971 Insurrection]] in a matter of months and becoming the first Sri Lankan army officer to be promoted to the rank of a [[General officer|four star General]]. He is known as the ''\"Father of the Armoured Corps\"'' and was [[Equerry|The Equerry]] to [[Elizabeth II|The Queen]] during her [[Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II|coronation]] in 1953.\n\n==Early life==\nSepala Attygalle was educated at the [[Royal College, Colombo]] where he became the [[Head Prefect|head prefect]], won colours in both [[Sport of athletics|athletics]] and [[rugby union|rugby]]; and was the Senior Sergeant of the [[Royal College, Colombo#Cadet Contingent|Cadet Contingent of Royal]]. After completing schooling, he entered the [[University College, Colombo]].<ref>[http://www.priu.gov.lk/news_update/Current_Affairs/CA200101/20010117SL_Army_commanders.htm Last post for two Generals] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107084513/http://www.priu.gov.lk/news_update/Current_Affairs/CA200101/20010117SL_Army_commanders.htm |date=7 January 2009 }}</ref> \n\nUThereafter he went on to study at the [[University of Ceylon]].\nHe graduated from the [[Staff College, Camberley]] in 1953 and the [[Imperial Defence College]] in 1966.\n\n==Military career==\n===Second World War===\nWith the outbreak of [[World War II]] seeking a [[Officer (armed forces)#United Kingdom|King's Commission]], he left his studies at the university college to joined as a [[Cadet Officer|cadet officer]] undergoing basic officer training at [[Diyatalawa]]. He took the [[Sword of Honour (Sandhurst)|sword of honour]] at the army passing out parade in 1941 and was commissioned as a [[second lieutenant]] in the [[Ceylon Light Infantry]]. He thereafter underwent advanced training in India.\n\n===Civil service===\nAfter the war, he was demobilized and joined the civil service serving as [[Assistant controller|Assistant Controller]] of Textiles and Assistant Controller of Exports and Imports.\n\n===Ceylon army===\nWith the formation of the new [[Ceylon Army]] in 1949 following the passing of the ''Army Act''; he joined it and was commissioned as a [[lieutenant]] in the 1 Battalion, [[Ceylon Light Infantry]] as a regular officer, promoted to the rank of [[Captain (land and air)|captain]] on the same day he was assigned was as the [[General Staff Officer]] - Grade 3 (GSO3), in the [[Army Headquarters, Ceylon]]. In 1950 he was appointed as an extra [[Aide-de-camp]] (ADC) to [[Herwald Ramsbotham, 1st Viscount Soulbury|Lord Soulbury]], the [[Governor General of Ceylon]], succeeding Major [[Bevis Bawa]]. He was promoted to rank of [[major]] in 1952.  \n\nIn mid 1952, he attended the Company Commanders' Course at the [[Warminster|School of Infantry, Warminster]] and the Land/Air Warfare Course at the [[School of Land/Air Warfare]]. Thereafter he was attached to the 1st Battalion, [[King's Own Yorkshire Light Infantry]], in Germany; serving with the [[Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe|NATO Forces in Europe]]. On his return he was re-assigned as a staff officer in the general staff at [[Army Headquarters (Sri Lanka)|army headquarters]].  \n\nIn 1953, he relinquished his staff appointment at the army headquarters and left for the [[United Kingdom]] to attend the [[Staff College, Camberley]]. On completing the staff course, he was seconded to the [[1st The Queen's Dragoon Guards]]. During this time he was appointed [[Equerry]] to HM [[Queen Elizabeth II]] at her coronation and also served as military liaison officer ([[Military attach\u00e9|military attach\u00e9]]) to the [[Sri Lankan High Commissioner to the United Kingdom|High Commissioner for Ceylon]] in the United Kingdom. On his return to Ceylon, he took up command of the [[Echelon Barracks]].\n\n===Ceylon Armoured Corps===\nOn 10 October 1955, Major D.S. Attygalle raised the 1st Reconnaissance (Recce) Squadron as the [[Cavalry|Cavalry Arm]] in the Ceylon Army in the lines of 1st The Queen's Dragoon Guards. On 17 December 1955 a Combined Services Buddhist Mission led by Major Attygalle left for [[Burma]] on board [[HMCyS Vijaya]], to represent the [[Armed Forces of Ceylon]] at the [[Buddha's Birthday|Buddha Jayanthi]] commemoration celebrations, and present a gift of a [[Jaya Sri Maha Bodhi|Bodhi tree sapling]]. In 1958, the [[Squadron (army)|recce squadron]] was expanded to a [[regiment]] and Attygalle was appointed as its first commanding officer with the rank of [[lieutenant colonel]]. The 1st Reconnaissance Regiment became the core of the [[Sri Lanka Armoured Corps|Ceylon Armoured Corps]].\n\n===TFAII and Chief of Staff===\nIn 1962, he was promoted to the rank of [[colonel]]; he took up command of the [[Panagoda Cantonment]], whilst serving as commanding officer, Ceylon Armoured Corps. Thereafter he became the commander of the [[Task Force Anti Illicit Immigration]] in 1963, later the inspector of training, Army Headquarters. He became the [[Chief of Staff]] of the army in 1964 after relinquishing command of the Ceylon Armoured Corps and relinquished command of the Task Force Anti Illicit Immigration in 1965.\n\n===Commander of the Army===\nOn 1 October 1967 [[Brigadier]] Don S. Attygalle took over as the Acting Commander of the Army after the retirement of [[Major General]] [[B.R. Heyn]]. Promoted to the rank of [[major general]], he was confirmed as [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Army]] shortly. Under his leadership the army crushed the [[1971 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|1971 Insurrection]] within two months, and he was promoted to the rank of [[lieutenant general]] on 4 April 1974, thus being the first officer of the [[Sri Lanka Army]] to hold this rank. When he retired on 13 October 1977, after having served for ten years as commander, he was promoted to the rank of [[General officer|general]], thus becoming the first Sri Lankan army officer to hold the rank of a four-star general and longest-serving Commander of the Army.\n\n==Later life==\n===Ministry of Defence===\nOn retirement from the army, he took up appointment as Additional Secretary, Ministry of Defence and Chief Co-ordinating Authority in the Ministry of Defence in 1977. \n\n===Secretary of Defence===\nIn the early 1980s, with the escalation of the [[Sri Lankan Civil War|Tamil Militancy]], he was appointed as [[permanent secretary]], [[Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka)|Ministry of Defence]] and served as National Defence Advisor to the [[President of Sri Lanka]]. He played a major role during the [[Vadamarachchi Operation]] until Indian intervention stopped it midway.  During this time he was the founding chairman, Air Ports and Aviation Services and chairman of [[Air Lanka]]. \n\n===High Commissioner to the United Kingdom===\nIn 1990 he was appointed as [[Sri Lankan High Commissioner to the United Kingdom|High Commissioner for Sri Lanka]] in the United Kingdom.\n\n===Death===\nHis [[military funeral]] in January 2001 was well attended by his family, friends and colleagues who gathered to mourn his loss.\n\n==Family== \nHe was married to Mrs Brighty Attygalle who died in July 2010, they had one son Suraj and two grandsons Damin and Shaminda. His brother was Dr Gamini Attygalle, [[FRCS]] a leading [[anaesthesiologist]] who was married to Kalyani Wijewardene, daughter of Don Walter T Wijewardene and sister of [[Upali Wijewardene]].<ref>[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/100103/Plus/plus_11.html A distinguished doctor who was respected for his rare qualities]</ref>\n\n==Decorations ==\nHe was made a Member of the [[Royal Victorian Order]] (Military Division) (MVO) by Her Majesty the Queen in recognition of the services rendered by him, during her Majesty's visit to Ceylon in 1954 which was later upgrade to lieutenant in 1984. For wartime service in World War II, he had earned the [[Defence Medal (United Kingdom)|Defence Medal]] and the [[War Medal 1939\u20131945]], and for service in the Ceylon Army, he received the [[Ceylon Armed Services Long Service Medal]], the [[Queen Elizabeth II Coronation Medal]] and the [[Ceylon Armed Services Inauguration Medal]]. For service in the Sri Lanka Army, he received the [[Republic of Sri Lanka Armed Services Medal]] and the [[Vadamarachchi Operation Medal]] for his later service as Secretary of Defence.\n\n===Honors===\n* Attygalle was promoted to the rank of [[General officer|general]] upon his retirement in 1977.\n* He was awarded the title [[Deshamanya]] from the Government of Sri Lanka.\n* He was a made a [[Royal Victorian Order|Member of the Royal Victorian Order]], which was later upgraded to Lieutenant.\n* Doctor of Literature (honorary) by the [[University of Sri Lanka]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sri Lanka Armoured Corps]]\n*[[Sri Lankan Non Career Diplomats]]\n*[[List of Sri Lankan non-career Permanent Secretaries]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080505203152/http://www.army.lk/co.php Parade Commander Major B.R. Heyn, CLI]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110904090717/http://www.armouredcorps.lk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=26:deshamanya-general-ds-atiygalle-mvo-idc-psc-d-litt&catid=7:retaired-senior-officers&Itemid=4 Father of the Armoured Corps]\n*[http://www.island.lk/2001/01/17/news05.html From Captain to Army Commander \u2014 Sepala Attygalle\u2019s illustrious career]\n*[http://www.rootsweb.com/~lkawgw/comcork.html rootsweb.com]\n*[http://suntimes.lk/040118/plus/appreciation.html SundayTimes Appreciation]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[http://ceylonmedals.com/attygalle.htm Deshamanya General Don Sepala Attygalle LVO ADC idc psc]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]]\n | before=[[B.R. Heyn]]\n | after=[[Denis Perera]]| years=1967 - 1977}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{succession box | title=Sri Lanka's High Commissioner to the United Kingdom | before=? | after=? | years= }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Commanders of the Sri Lankan Army}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Attygalle, D.S.}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan generals]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese civil servants]]\n[[Category:Equerries]]\n[[Category:Lieutenants of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Royal College, Colombo]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Ceylon (Colombo)]]\n[[Category:Ceylonese military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of Sri Lanka to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Defence Studies]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Staff College, Camberley]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Sri Lanka Army]]\n[[Category:King's Own Yorkshire Light Infantry officers]]\n[[Category:1st The Queen's Dragoon Guards officers]]\n[[Category:Sri Lanka Armoured Corps officers]]\n[[Category:Permanent secretaries of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan military attach\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:Deshamanya]]\n", "name_user": "Dan arndt", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove flagicon from infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sepala_Attygalle"}
